item.description:
### Background

Before we started implementing JSONAPI payload support for _POST_ and _PUT_ requests you were required to provide all information regarding relationships when making a request. This required consumers of the API to make additional API calls to gather the required information making it cumbersom to use.

#### Example

You have a `Target` and has a currently relationship to `Agents` 1, 2, and 3. Now you wanted to also add `Agent` 4 to the `Target`. That meant you needed to provided `Agent` ids 1, 2, 3, and 4. Otherwise providing just `Agent` 4 would remove `Agents` 1, 2, and 3.

``` json
{
  "target": {
    ...
    "agent_ids": [4] // Agents 1, 2, 3 will be removed.
    ...
  }
}
{
  "target": {
    ...
    "agent_ids": [1,2,3,4] // Agent 4 is added to 1, 2, and, 3.
    ...
  }
}

 ```

### Upserts with JSONAPI

With JSONAPI payloads for _POST_ and _PUT_ requests we can now support upserting of associations. That means consumers of the API will no longer have to provide all ids of an association in order to add or remove them.

### Example

You have a `Target` and has a currently relationship to `Agents` 1, 2, and 3. Now you wanted to also add `Agent` 4 to the `Target`. This means you can upsert only `Agent` 4 to the `Target` without needing to know the currently related `Agents`.

``` json
{
  "data": {
    "id": "1",
    "type": "target",
    "attributes": {
      ...
    },
    "relationships": {
      "agents": {
        "data": [
          { 
            "id": "4",
            "type": "agent" // Upsert Agent 4 to add to Target.
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  }
}

 ```

### Removals with JSONAPI

Like wise with JSONAPI payloads for _POST_ and _PUT_ requests we can request the removal of relationships. That means consumers of the API will no longer have to provide all ids of the remaining related `Agents`.

### Example

You have a `Target` and has a currently relationship to `Agents` 1, 2, 3, and 4. Now you wanted to remove `Agent` 4 from the `Target`. This means you can remove only `Agent` 4 to the `Target` without needing to know the all the `Agents` that should remain related.

``` json
{
  "data": {
    "id": "1",
    "type": "target",
    "attributes": {
      ...
    },
    "relationships": {
      "agents": {
        "data": [
          { 
            "id": "4",
            "type": "agent",
            "method": "remove" // Add 'method' with value 'remove' to remove Agent 4.
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  }
}

 ```
